'Now I am awake'
Will Cohu reviews Forever Today by Deborah Wearing
Will Cohu
12:01AM GMT 30 Jan 2005
Comments
It is 20 years since the conductor Clive Wearing woke up from a fevered sleep with the most severe case of amnesia ever documented. A freak dose of herpes simplex – the innocuous virus that causes cold sores – had wreaked havoc with the temporal lobes of his brain. Clive could remember how to read music, he could remember things that had happened years before, but he had no consciousness of what had just happened. Life became an agonising, ceaseless reawakening, which he documented in his diaries: 7:46am I WAKE FOR THE FIRST TIME7:47am THIS ILLNESS HAS BEEN LIKE DEATH TILL NOW ALL SENSES WORK 8:07am I AM AWAKE 8:31am NOW I AM AWAKE 9:06am NOW I AM AWAKE 11:37am NOW I AM PERFECTLY COMPLETELY AWAKE (1st TIME) Deborah Wearing stuck with her husband through 10 years of this. It must have been awful to witness such confusion engulfing someone she loved but, despite his condition, Clive was still Clive – "living evidence that you could lose almost everything you ever knew about yourself and still be yourself" – and he loved her above all else. This was a mixed blessing, for she could not free herself from him, and his infantile dependence dominated her life. It sounds as if he had always been somewhat dependent. Clive, who was nearly 20 years older than Deborah, was talented but scatty and perverse in his career choices. She met him when she sang in one of the choirs he conducted; their relationship was emotionally profound but financially precarious and geared towards Clive's choices. After he became sick, Deborah abandoned her own life, immersing herself in neuropsychology and founding a charity for amnesia sufferers. Clive was the subject of films and conferences, and Deborah was in the undesirable position of having a career made on the back of her husband's illness. Inevitably, she cracked. Leaving Clive in hospital, she obtained a divorce and fled to America. She tried acting, creative writing and performance poetry and had a couple of unsatisfactory affairs with damaged Vietnam veterans masquerading as sensitive sorts. It's a section of the book that makes uncomfortable reading; Deborah, who writes beautifully about her husband, is uncomfortable when exploring herself; it's as if she can't get the perspective right – is she comic or tragic? – and her images have an over-compensatory tenderness. In one disastrous moment of empathy, she compares herself to Jackie Kennedy with her husband's brains all over her, holding "that most private of all her husband's parts wetting her white cotton glove until someone took it from her at the hospital". In the end, the constant in her life was Clive, who still loved her, and called her back to him with heart-breaking sincerity. She returned to England, took a job and renewed her marriage vows. "Perhaps it is only when the rest of life comes apart that the strength of love becomes visible," she concludes. But how was she able to resign herself to this curtailed life? Towards the end of this remarkable, bemusing story, there is a disquieting passage. In a couple of paragraphs, Deborah describes how, one miserable day, she asked a Christian friend to pray for her and felt the Holy Spirit come down the telephone wire "like a force and like honey". Thereafter, it all became simple. "I wasn't alone," she writes. Faith gave her power and she began to see "deep changes in Clive" as she prayed for him. Her religious experience casts a retrospective shadow on her narrative, which seems to have been leading to her conversion. Even Clive's constant awakening is the intimation of a greater resurrection. Once introduced, religion takes control of a story like this and reduces human experience to metaphor. Her prayers may well have helped Clive but, equally, his partial recovery, to the point where he is able to recognise his problems and compensate, is testament to the human potential for painful, ingenious self-creation. And it is testament to her extraordinary strength and fidelity to the man. There is also a sense of the divine at work that is not always benign. For in a peculiar way, Deborah Wearing did get what she wanted. She describes how her early days with Clive were soured by her jealousy of his previous marriage and old girlfriends. She wanted him to have known no one before her, and her wish was granted. Deborah did become Clive's first, last and only love, and it was unbearable. Books
