The FSA letter read: "We wish to understand better the ability of funds to meet potential redemption demands. We understand that the liquidity of many of the instruments in which such funds invest may be sufficiently low to make large trades difficult without material trading costs. "Concerns have been raised with us that market liquidity has the potential to be impacted further as a result of the implementation of future global regulations. The market for these funds has been strong in recent years, and we wish to understand the extent to which a reversal of this trend could create risks for investors."
Chris Bowie, fixed-interest manager at Ignis, admitted that it was a "very challenging time" for bond managers. Mr Bowie, who told Telegraph readers last month that investors should not be buying bonds right now, said: "Prior to the banking crisis I could have turned over my portfolio in three months – now it takes much longer," he said. "Instead of being able to push through £150m in a day you have to stagger it, £3m here, £4m there. You have to manage positions much more slowly."
The reduced liquidity is caused in part by investment banks having significantly less capital to allocate to corporate bond trades. Owing to regulation and reduced cash flow, investment banks have just a quarter of the cash they had 12 months ago for trades, making it harder for managers to sell bonds in the market.
Add to this a significantly reduced number of new bond issues and you can see why liquidity has become an issue.
"If we have a eurozone banking crisis and there is a rush for redemptions, we could see a similar liquidity crisis to the one experienced by the commercial property market in 2008," said Mr Bowie. "Investors simply won't be able to access their cash."
Artemis bond manager James Foster agreed. "If there is a rush for the door, caused either by a rise in interest rates or by problems in the eurozone, you would potentially be faced with a redemption freeze, as there would be no bond buyer on the other side," he said.
Five years ago, tens of thousands of investors were stuck in commercial property funds because liquidity dried up – managers couldn't sell holdings and investors were forced to wait up to six months to get their money out. Hefty exit fees were also applied.
Ian Spreadbury, who runs the £3bn Fidelity Moneybuilder Income fund, the fourth largest corporate bond fund in Britain, said he held a "liquidity bucket" in his portfolio, made up of cash and gilts. "In a situation when there were substantial outflows, if you were fully invested in corporate bonds you would struggle to pay investors," he said.
Financial advisers are warning their clients off investing new money in the sector, while those already in the funds are advised not to panic but to keep an eye on the situation.
"At the moment, trading desks are telling us that demand for quality credit is still outstripping supply and liquidity in sterling terms is challenging," said Brian Dennehy of FundExpert.co.uk. "This liquidity squeeze is continuing to drive down the yield on quality credit, forcing prices up, and looks set to continue for a while yet."
Gary Potter, a fund of funds manager at Thames River Capital, said: "Corporate debt total return is not compelling by any means versus other asset classes. It is harder to manage these bond funds compared with when they were small and performance can be compromised – the bigger the oil tanker, the harder it is to turn around."
M & G moved to play down its decision. Richard Woolnough, who runs the two funds, rejected liquidity concerns, claiming that the group simply wanted to discourage inflows so that he could continue to "effectively execute" his ideas. "We are looking to the future and to do the best by our existing investors," he said. Featured Isa / Investment platforms »
